<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Definitions before governance</h2>
  <p>Article Seven makes definition a public responsibility. Conversation, consent, law, and repair all fail when the key words slide around unseen.</p>
  <p>A circle applying this article should keep a definition ledger. Each important term should include its current meaning, who proposed it, where it is disputed, and what cases test the edge.</p>
  <p>When a definition is absent, someone must propose a standard. When the proposed standard is disputed, the dispute itself becomes part of the record.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> Define the terms</p>
  <p>Article Seven says: where any would converse, let them first define the terms.</p>
  <p>That sounds simple until you notice how many fights are really fights over hidden definitions. Safety. Harm. Freedom. Consent. Authority. Adult. Care. These words do not govern honestly if no one knows what they mean.</p>
  <p>The article says that when a definition is missing or disputed, a standard must be devised. But the footnote warns us: no rule set abolishes discernment.</p>
  <p>So definitions are not cages. They are shared tools. They let people know what conversation they are actually in, what they are consenting to, and where disagreement remains real.</p>
</section>
